<section id="sect-00001">
<title>Acid-Catalyzed Epoxide Opening</title>
<para id="para-00001">Epoxides are cleaved by treatment with acid just as other ethers are, but under much milder conditions because of ring strain. As we saw in <link document="m00095"/>, dilute aqueous acid at room temperature is sufficient for facilitating the hydrolysis of epoxides to give 1,2-diols, also called <emphasis effect="italics">vicinal glycols.</emphasis> (The word <emphasis effect="italics">vicinal</emphasis> means “adjacent,” and a <emphasis effect="italics">glycol</emphasis> is a diol.) The epoxide cleavage takes place by S<sub>N</sub>2-like backside attack of a nucleophile on the protonated epoxide, giving a trans-1,2-diol as product.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00001">
<media alt="An illustration shows 2 chemical reactions. The first reaction shows 1 2-Epoxycyclohexane in the presence of a hydronium ion yielding two intermediate compounds where the first one in the presence of water will yield the second intermediate. This in the presence of water yields “trans-1 2-Cyclohexanediol (86%) and a hydronium ion. The structure of 1 2-Epoxycyclohexane shows a cyclohexane with C1 and C2 dash bonded to a hydrogen each and wedge bonded to a common oxygen atom having four electrons. The first intermediate shows a cyclohexane with C1 and C2 dash bonded to a hydrogen atom each and wedge bonded to a common oxygen cation (pink) bonded to hydrogen atom (blue). The oxygen shows two electrons. The oxygen of water shows four electrons and an arrow from the electrons points to C2. An arrow from the C2-O bond points to O. The second intermediate shows a cyclohexane with C1 dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (O is pink and H is blue). C2 is wedge bonded to a hydrogen atom and single bonded to oxygen cation bonded to two hydrogens. The oxygen of water shows four electrons and an arrow from the electrons points to a hydrogen bonded to oxygen cation. An arrow from the H-O cation bond points to O cation. The structure of trans-1 2-Cyclohexanediol shows a cyclohexane ring with C1 dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (O is pink and H is blue). C2 is wedge bonded to a hydrogen atom and dash bonded to blue hydroxyl group. Text of the second reaction reads: Recall the following. The reaction shows a cyclohexene reacting in the presence of pink bromine yielding an intermediate which in the presence of blue bromine anion with eight electrons yields trans-1 2-Dibromocyclohexane. The cyclohexene shows a single double bond and is bonded to two hydrogens. The structure of the intermediate shows a cyclohexene ring with C1 and C2 dash bonded to a hydrogen atom each. C1 and C2 are wedge bonded to a common Bromine cation; an arrow from the electrons of bromine ion points to C2. An arrow from the C2-Br bond points to Br. trans-1 2-Dibromocyclohexane shows a cyclohexane with C1 dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a pink bromine. C2 is wedge bonded to a hydrogen atom and dash bonded to blue bromine.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_001.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00002">Epoxides can also be opened by reaction with acids other than H<sub>3</sub>O<sup>+</sup>. If anhydrous HX is used, for instance, an epoxide is converted into a trans halohydrin.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where an epoxide reacts in the presence of ether and “HX” to yield a trans 2-halocyclohexanol. The epoxide shows a cyclohexane with C1 and C2 dash bonded to a hydrogen each and wedge bonded to a common oxygen atom. In HX H is pink and X is green. The structure of trans 2-halocyclohexanol shows a cyclohexane with C1 dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a pink hydroxyl group. C2 is dash bonded to green X and wedge bonded to a hydrogen. X may be F Br Cl or I.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_002.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00003">The regiochemistry of acid-catalyzed ring-opening depends on the epoxide’s structure, and a mixture of products is often formed. When both epoxide carbon atoms are either primary or secondary, attack of the nucleophile occurs primarily at the less highly substituted site: an S<sub>N</sub>2-like result. When one of the epoxide carbon atoms is tertiary, however, nucleophilic attack occurs primarily at the <emphasis effect="italics">more</emphasis> highly substituted site—an S<sub>N</sub>1-like result. Thus, 1,2-epoxypropane reacts with HCl to give primarily 1-chloro-2-propanol, but 2-methyl-1,2-epoxypropane gives 2-chloro-2-methyl-1- propanol as the major product.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows 2 chemical reactions. The first reaction shows “1 2-Epoxypropane” in the presence of hydrochloric acid (hydrogen shown in pink and chlorine shown in green) and ether yielding “1-Chloro-2-propanol (90%)” and “2-Chloro-1-propanol (10%).” The structure of 1 2-Epoxypropane shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other and are also bonded to a common oxygen atom (shown in pink). The first carbon atom labeled “Secondary” is bonded to a methyl group and a hydrogen atom. The second carbon atom labeled “Primary” is bonded to 2 hydrogen atoms. The structure of 1-Chloro-2-propanol shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other. The first carbon atom is also bonded to a hydrogen atom methyl group and a hydroxyl group (shown in pink). The second carbon atom is bonded to 2 hydrogen atoms and a chlorine atom (shown in green). The structure of 2-Chloro-1-propanol shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other. The first carbon atom is bonded to a hydrogen atom methyl group and a chlorine atom (shown in green). The second carbon atom is bonded to 2 hydrogen atoms and a hydroxyl group (shown in pink). The second reaction shows “2-Methyl-1 2-epoxypropane” in the presence of hydrochloric acid (Hydrogen atom shown in pink and chlorine atom shown in green) and ether yielding “2-Chloro-2-methyl-1-propanol (60%)” and “1-Chloro-2-methyl-2-propanol (40%).” The structure of 2-Methyl-1 2-epoxypropane shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other and also bonded to a common oxygen atom (shown in pink). The first carbon atom labeled “Tertiary” is also bonded to 2 methyl groups. The second carbon atom labeled “Primary” is also bonded to 2 hydrogen atoms. The structure of 2-Chloro-2-methyl-1-propanol shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other. The first carbon atom is bonded to a chlorine atom (shown in green) and 2 methyl groups. The second carbon atom is bonded to a hydroxyl group (shown in pink) and 2 hydrogen atoms. The structure of 1-Chloro-2-methyl-2-propanol shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other. The first carbon atom is bonded to a hydroxyl group (shown in pink) and 2 methyl groups. The second carbon atom is bonded to a chlorine atom (shown in green) and 2 hydrogen atoms.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_003.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00004">The mechanisms of these acid-catalyzed epoxide openings are more complex than they initially appear. They seem to be neither purely S<sub>N</sub>1 nor S<sub>N</sub>2 but instead to be midway between the two extremes and to have characteristics of both. For instance, take the reaction of 1,2-epoxy-1-methylcyclohexane with HBr, shown in <link target-id="fig-00004"/>. The reaction yields only a single stereoisomer of 2-bromo-2-methylcyclohexanol in which the –Br and –OH groups are trans, an S<sub>N</sub>2-like result caused by backside displacement of the epoxide oxygen. But the fact that Br<sup>–</sup> attacks the more hindered tertiary side of the epoxide rather than the less hindered secondary side is an S<sub>N</sub>1-like result in which the more stable, tertiary carbocation is involved.</para>
<para id="para-00005">Evidently, the transition state for acid-catalyzed epoxide opening has an S<sub>N</sub>2-like geometry but also has a high degree of S<sub>N</sub>1-like carbocationic character. Because the positive charge in the protonated epoxide is shared by the more highly substituted carbon atom, backside attack of Br<sup>–</sup> occurs at the more highly substituted site.</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where 1 2-epoxy-1-methylcyclohexane reacts in the presence of with Hydrogen bromide and yields a more stable tertiary carbocation that further yields 2-bromo-2-methylcyclohexanol. The structure of a secondary carbocation that is not formed is shown to yield a product. The structure of 1 2-epoxy-1-methylcyclohexane shows a cyclohexane ring dash bonded to a methyl group at C1 and hydrogen atom at C2. These are wedge bonded to a common oxygen atom (shown in pink) with 2 pairs of electrons. The tertiary carbocation shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group at C1 and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (shown in pink) and dash bonded to a hydrogen atom at C2. C1 is a cation. A pink curved arrow is shown from a bromine anion (shown in green) to C1. It is continued as dotted line up to the hydroxyl group bonded to C2. The structure of 2-bromo-2-methylcyclohexanol shows a cyclohexane single bonded to a bromine atom (shown in green) and wedge bonded to a methyl group at C1. C2 is single bonded to a hydrogen atom and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (shown in pink). The secondary carbocation shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (shown in pink) at C1; C2 a cation is bonded to a hydrogen atom. A pink arrow is shown from a bromium anion up to C2 and continues as a dotted line up to the hydroxyl group bonded to C1. This further yields a cyclohexane with C1 dash bonded to a methyl group and wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group (pink); C2 is dash bonded to a bromine atom (green) and wedge bonded to a hydrogen atom.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_004.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Ring-opening of 1,2-epoxy-1-methylcyclohexane with HBr</emphasis>. There is a high degree of S<sub>N</sub>1-like carbocation character in the transition state, which leads to backside attack of the nucleophile at the tertiary center and to formation of a product isomer that has –Br and –OH groups trans.</caption>
</figure>
<example id="exam-00001">
<title>Predicting the Product of Epoxide Ring-Opening</title>
<para id="para-00006">Predict the major product of the following reaction:</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction whose yield is to be predicted. The reaction shows a cyclohexane structure bonded to a 3-membered ring with a pink oxygen atom reacting in the presence of hydrochloric acid and ether.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_005.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00007"><title><span class="red-text">Strategy</span></title> Identify the substitution pattern of the two epoxide carbon atoms. In this case, one carbon is secondary and one is primary. Then recall the guidelines for epoxide cleavages. An epoxide with only primary and secondary carbons usually undergoes cleavage by S<sub>N</sub>2-like attack of a nucleophile on the less hindered carbon, but an epoxide with a tertiary carbon atom usually undergoes cleavage by backside attack on the more hindered carbon. In this case, an S<sub>N</sub>2 cleavage of the primary C–O epoxide bond will occur.</para>
<para id="para-00008"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where an epoxide reacts in the presence of hydrochloric acid (hydrogen atom shown in pink and chlorine atom shown in green) and ether to yield a product. The structure of the epoxide shows a cyclohexane bonded to the secondary carbon of a 3-membered ring that shows a pink oxygen atom. The primary carbon where reaction occurs is labeled. The structure of the product shows a cyclohexane bonded to a 2-carbon chain. C1 is bonded to a pink hydroxyl group. C2 is bonded to a green chlorine atom.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_006.jpg"/>
</media>
