<section id="sect-00003">
<title>Base-Catalyzed Epoxide Opening</title>
<para id="para-00011">Unlike other ethers, epoxide rings can be cleaved by bases and nucleophiles as well as by acid. Although an ether oxygen is normally a poor leaving group in an S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction (<link document="m00124"/>), the strain of the three-membered ring causes epoxides to react with hydroxide ion at elevated temperatures.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00007">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where “Methylenecyclohexane oxide” reacts with hydroxyl ion in the presence of water at 100 degrees centigrade and yields an intermediate compound which in the presence of water yields “1-Hydroxymethylcyclohexanol (70%)” and a pink hydroxyl ion. The structure of Methylenecyclohexane oxide shows a cyclohexane with C1 bonded to an oxygen atom and methylene group. The oxygen atom and methylene group are bonded forming a three-membered ring. The hydroxyl ion shows six electrons. An arrow from these electrons points to the methylene group. An arrow from the bond between the methylene group and oxygen points to the oxygen. The structure of the intermediate compound shows a cyclohexane with C1 bonded to a pink oxygen anion and hydroxymethyl group whose hydroxyl group is shown in blue. The structure of 1-Hydroxymethyl cyclohexanol shows a cyclohexane with C1 bonded to a pink hydroxyl group and hydroxymethyl group whose hydroxyl group is shown in blue.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_009.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00012">Base-catalyzed epoxide opening is a typical S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction in which attack of the nucleophile takes place at the less hindered epoxide carbon. For example, 1,2-epoxypropane reacts with ethoxide ion exclusively at the less highly substituted, primary carbon to give 1-ethoxy-2-propanol.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00008">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction of “1 2-epoxypropane” in the presence of ethanol and ethoxide ion to yield “1-Ethoxy-2-propanol (83%).” The structure of 1 2-epoxypropane shows 2 carbon atoms bonded to each other and bonded to a common oxygen atom (shown in pink) forming a three-membered ring. The first carbon atom labeled “No attack here (secondary)” is also bonded to a hydrogen atom and a methyl group. The second carbon atom is bonded to 2 hydrogen atoms. An arrow from the ethoxide ion points to the carbon that is bonded to two hydrogens. An arrow from the bond between this carbon and oxygen points to oxygen. The structure of 1-Ethoxy-2-propanol shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to a methylene group that is bonded to a blue oxygen bonded to a blue ethyl group. The methine group is bonded to a hydroxyl group that shows pink oxygen and blue hydrogen.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_010.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00013">Many different nucleophiles can be used for epoxide opening, including amines (RNH<sub>2</sub> or R<sub>2</sub>NH) and Grignard reagents (RMgX). An example of an amine reacting with an epoxide occurs in the commercial synthesis of metoprolol, a so-called <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-blocker that is used for treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, hypertension, and heart attacks. <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-Blockers are among the most widely prescribed drugs in the world.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction of an epoxide in the presence of an amine to yield an intermediate compound which in the presence of hydrogen and a catalyst yields metoprolol. The structure of the epoxide shows a benzene ring with its top bonded to an oxygen atom which is further bonded to an oxygen atom (shown in pink) that is part of a cyclopropane. The bottom of the benzene ring is bonded to a methine group that is bonded to a methylene group bonded to a methoxide on the left. On the right the methine group is bonded to an oxygen atom bonded to a carbonyl group and bonded to a methyl group. The amine is shown in blue and shows an amino group with a pair of electrons bonded to a methine group that is bonded to two methyl groups. A pink curved arrow from these electrons points to a carbon of the cyclopropane ring. In the ring an arrow from the CH2-O bond points to O. The structure of the intermediate compound is similar to the reactant but the benzene ring is bonded to an oxygen at the top that is further bonded to C1 of a 4-carbon chain that shows a blue nitrogen monohydride between C2 and C3. C1 is bonded to a hydroxyl group that shows pink O and blue H. C3 of the chain is bonded to a blue methyl group. C3 and C4 are shown in blue. The structure of metoprolol is similar to the intermediate compound but the benzene ring is bonded to a methylene group at the bottom that is further bonded to another methylene group bonded to a methoxide group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_011.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00014">A similar nucleophilic ring-opening occurs when epoxides are treated with Grignard reagents. Ethylene oxide is frequently used, thereby allowing the conversion of a Grignard reagent into a primary alcohol having two more carbons than the starting alkyl halide. 1-Bromobutane, for example, is converted into 1-hexanol by reaction of its Grignard reagent with ethylene oxide.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00010">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where blue “Butylmagnesium bromide” reacts with “Ethylene oxide” in the presence of an ether solvent and a pink hydronium cation and yields “1-Hexanol (62%).” The structure of butylmagnesium bromide shows a 4-carbon chain bonded to MgBr. The structure of ethylene oxide shows a 3-membered ring with a pink oxygen and two methylene groups. 1-Hexanol shows a blue butyl group bonded to a chain of two methylene groups and then a pink hydroxyl group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_06_012.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
